04387nmm a2200613Ia 9780801464133DE-B159720240328111612.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240328t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979575653  a97808014641337 a10.7591/97808014641332doi  a(DE-B1597)478428  a(OCoLC)781542959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD453b.M55 201604a940.31122231 aMiller, Gregory D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Shadow of the Past :bReputation and Military Alliances before the First World War /cGregory D. Miller. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b2 line drawings, 11 tables, 1 chart/graph  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCornell Studies in Security Affairs00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. Alliances and Reputation in International Relations -- t2. Reliability and Alliance Behavior -- t3. The End of Splendid Isolation: British Pursuit of an Ally, 1901–1905 -- t4. The First Moroccan Crisis: Testing the Anglo-French Entente, 1904–1907 -- t5. The Bosnia-Herzegovina Crisis: Expanding the Entente, 1907–1911 -- t6. The Agadir Crisis: Rolling toward War, 1910–1914 -- t7. Summary and Expansion of Findings -- tAppendixes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Shadow of the Past, Gregory D. Miller examines the role that reputation plays in international politics, emphasizing the importance of reliability—confidence that, based on past political actions, a country will make good on its promises—in the formation of military alliances. Challenging recent scholarship that focuses on the importance of credibility—a state’s reputation for following through on its threats—Miller finds that reliable states have much greater freedom in forming alliances than those that invest resources in building military force but then use it inconsistently. To explore the formation and maintenance of alliances based on reputation, Miller draws on insights from both political science and business theory to track the evolution of great power relations before the First World War. He starts with the British decision to abandon "splendid isolation" in 1900 and examines three crises—the First Moroccan Crisis (1905–6), the Bosnia-Herzegovina Crisis (1908–9), and the Agadir Crisis (1911)—leading up to the war. He determines that states with a reputation for being a reliable ally have an easier time finding other reliable allies, and have greater autonomy within their alliances, than do states with a reputation for unreliability. Further, a history of reliability carries long-term benefits, as states tend not to lose allies even when their reputation declines.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAlliances. 0aReputation (Law). 4aHistory. 4aMilitary History. 4aSecurity Studies.  ainternational relations, international alliances, overseas alliances, reliability and alliances, state credibility, military strategy, political science.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146413340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801464133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801464133/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles